video_title: Peter Attia: Anti-aging Cure No One Talks About! 50% Chance You’ll Die In A Year If This Happens!
comment_text:
You don't need to spend thousands, here my regimen 

1. As warm up, walk for 5 min on treadmill at 1.5 incline at 3 mph.
2. At 5min-10 adjust to 11 incline at 2.7 mph.
3. Walk for .5 mile back at 1.5 incline and 3 mph.
4. At 1.5 incline run at 6 mph for 1/3 or a mile or roughly .30.
5. Walk at 1.5 for .5 mile.
6. Change incline to 11 again for 5 min at 2.7. 
7. Walk at 1.5 for .5 mile.
8. Run at 1.5 at 7 mph for .2 mile or .3 mile.

Alternate between walking and running, between 6 mph and 7 mph. If you get sore calves run at incline of 7-9 at 6 mph for shorter distances. 
Repeat this until you can do it consistently under a hour with at least 3.5 miles total and burned 620-650 calories.

If you body adapt just crank either the speed by .5 or 1 or adjust the incline by a point or two. 

Why does it work? You spend only 1 hours, you working that heart and you are burning calories/fat. You not overly stressed mentally or physically but it's definitely a work out! 

Everyone looking will think it's easy but it's not. If you reach this point you  can congratulate yourself and keep pushing. 😊 Oh, you should not have to stop at anytime during the hour!

At my age my heart rate is constantly switching between 130-165. Burning roughly 177 calories per mile, not an easy feat.

If you really want to push it, do this while at fasted state. 😮

Even a "non serious" tear that didn't require surgery had me on crutches for 2 weeks and in physio for 3 months, just to return to get back to squatting "properly". Properly here meaning I'm no longer doing triples at 180kg and looking to beat my gyms squat record. Properly meaning Doing 5x5 at 60kg and doing linear progression of 2.5kg per leg day and evaluating it. 4 months after first squatting properly again and 140kg is no longer my final warm up, it looks like it's going to be close to my max. 4 months after and I'm questioning if it's even worth me continuing to train powerlifting giving my genetics for bench are beyond appalling, and slipping over might have robbed me of ever being able to do a remotely serious squat again. 

Lesson of the story is falling can FUCK. YOU. UP. No matter your age.

comment_text: The reason grip strength correlates to higher longevity is to do with general labor. Most day-to-day tasks, whether it's or fixing things up around the house or what you do for a living with your hands… They involve your hands. Keeping busiest is key.  The muscles involved with hand movement do not atrophy to the degree of the larger muscles. This is the basis of what is colloquially referred to as "old man strength".  They may not be doing the high intensity, vigourous activities that require the larger muscles, but they are still keeping busy. They are still fixing things, tidying things up, putsing around etc.  some motion is infinitely better than none when it comes to ageing folks.  This is where that correlation comes in. It is an indirect and a general proxy for physical activity, both in older years as well as what the person did physically their whole lives; in the gym, on the field, at home or at work.

video_title: Peter Attia: Anti-aging Cure No One Talks About! 50% Chance You’ll Die In A Year If This Happens!
comment_text:
Key Takeaways with Timestamps
(00:00) The “Marginal Decade” Concept
Dr. Peter Attia stresses preparing for your final decade of life—when the body is most vulnerable. Many only realize the importance of health when it's too late.

(00:56) VO2 Max as a Predictor of Longevity
Your VO2 max (maximum oxygen consumption) is the strongest measurable predictor of lifespan. Those in the top 2% have a 400% lower mortality risk than those in the bottom 25%.

(11:58) Exercise Preserves Mitochondrial and Muscle Function
People who stay active maintain better mitochondrial health, muscle mass, and strength—critical factors in slowing aging.

(21:19) Testosterone & Sleep
Testosterone production is closely tied to quality sleep. Sleep deprivation significantly lowers testosterone, as well as insulin sensitivity.

(24:41) Sleep Deprivation’s Metabolic Damage
A study showed that just 10–14 days of sleeping only 4 hours/night led to a 50% reduction in insulin sensitivity, a precursor to metabolic disease.

(36:30) Injury Prevention & Tendon Training
As people age, they often retain strength but lose tendon elasticity. Incorporating jumping and plyometric movements helps maintain tendon health.

(42:54) Fall Risk After Age 65
Falls become a leading cause of injury and death past age 65. Grip strength and balance training are essential to reduce this risk.

(55:12) Oxygen & ATP Production
The body’s ability to produce ATP (cellular energy) depends heavily on oxygen. Without it, the body shuts down in minutes—emphasizing the role of aerobic fitness.

(1:02:33) Healthspan vs. Lifespan
Attia emphasizes quality of life over simply living longer—training for strength, endurance, and metabolic health improves both lifespan and healthspan.

(1:20:14) Strength Training Improves Bone Density
In studies like the LYFTMORE study, heavy resistance training significantly improved bone density in women with osteoporosis.

video_title: Peter Attia: Anti-aging Cure No One Talks About! 50% Chance You’ll Die In A Year If This Happens!
comment_text: BMD misses 30% of patients who are osteoporotic because it only measures density. Trabecular Bone Score which can be run at the same time with the BMD scan provides the assessment of bone microarchitecture which is the quality of the bone. BMD +TBS provides the full picture of bone health. The TBS score tells you whether your bone is normal, partially degraded or fully degraded. Two people can be osteopenic based on BMD-t scores alone while the bone microarchitecture can be fully degraded in one of those patients meaning that patient is at a high risk for fracture. TBS is FDA approved, reimbursed by Medicare and Aetna, and is already integrated into all DXA scanners in the USA.

video_title: Peter Attia: Anti-aging Cure No One Talks About! 50% Chance You’ll Die In A Year If This Happens!
comment_text:
Key Takeaways with Timestamps
(00:00) The “Marginal Decade” Concept
Dr. Peter Attia stresses preparing for your final decade of life—when the body is most vulnerable. Many only realize the importance of health when it's too late.

(00:56) VO2 Max as a Predictor of Longevity
Your VO2 max (maximum oxygen consumption) is the strongest measurable predictor of lifespan. Those in the top 2% have a 400% lower mortality risk than those in the bottom 25%.

(11:58) Exercise Preserves Mitochondrial and Muscle Function
People who stay active maintain better mitochondrial health, muscle mass, and strength—critical factors in slowing aging.

(21:19) Testosterone & Sleep
Testosterone production is closely tied to quality sleep. Sleep deprivation significantly lowers testosterone, as well as insulin sensitivity.

(24:41) Sleep Deprivation’s Metabolic Damage
A study showed that just 10–14 days of sleeping only 4 hours/night led to a 50% reduction in insulin sensitivity, a precursor to metabolic disease.

(36:30) Injury Prevention & Tendon Training
As people age, they often retain strength but lose tendon elasticity. Incorporating jumping and plyometric movements helps maintain tendon health.

(42:54) Fall Risk After Age 65
Falls become a leading cause of injury and death past age 65. Grip strength and balance training are essential to reduce this risk.

(55:12) Oxygen & ATP Production
The body’s ability to produce ATP (cellular energy) depends heavily on oxygen. Without it, the body shuts down in minutes—emphasizing the role of aerobic fitness.

(1:02:33) Healthspan vs. Lifespan
Attia emphasizes quality of life over simply living longer—training for strength, endurance, and metabolic health improves both lifespan and healthspan.

(1:20:14) Strength Training Improves Bone Density
In studies like the LYFTMORE study, heavy resistance training significantly improved bone density in women with osteoporosis.

video_title: Peter Attia: Anti-aging Cure No One Talks About! 50% Chance You’ll Die In A Year If This Happens!
comment_text:
I have parents in their late 70s. My mom STARTED exercising (after years of back issues and yo yo dieting) at 63- committing to couch to 5K. Finished her first race and won (only entry in the 60+ age group for that race). Kept at it. Won 5 and 10K races into her 70s. Got off many meds. She also added resistance training. Dad joined her. Both ran their first half marathon at71, second at 72.

Both doing extremely well now. Sadly, many of their friends have died or live in much worse conditions. But them taking their health seriously and taking action has been a gift to themselves and all of those who love them. They live better than many of their peers- and even when an injury occurs (my dad had a nasty shoulder injury slipping on a dock)- they heal much better than anticipated (they are also 100% committed to any PT prescribed).

Of course it is better to start as early as possible, but it is never too late. The things you can do to take agency for your own health is much better than almost any prescription could ever provide do you.

On a personal note, my own cholesterol and fasting glucose was higher than normal but not in an area of concern for my MD, but reading Dr. Attia's book, Outlive, I advocated for myself to my MD to proactively  put me on a statin and metformin to mitigate these conditions (while also exercising regularly, being more mindful of my eating and supplementing to try to raise my good cholesterol) and that has had a profound impact on my health.

Her health has been going downhill ever since; she gets blood clots in her legs now and her legs and feet swell. She was really healthy and mobile until that fall and even still played tennis until then and was an avid bike rider and hiker. She was 57 when she fell.

comment_text:
I'm convinced forever chemicals are a key culprit to a lot of what ails us as a society. Forever chemicals are  EDC's = Endocrine Disrupting Chemicals.  As the name suggests, they wreak havoc on our endocrine system, which is the system of glands in our bodies that produce & release hormones.  EDC's are virtually unavoidable in modern society -  most of us have unknowingly been exposed to them & have ingested them our entire lives...  via water, food, cosmetics, soaps, lotions, fragrances,  non-stick cookware,  plastic food utensils, waterproof clothes, plastic/plastic coated food containers... so so many things we come into contact with daily.   All of our endocrine/hormonal systems have been under silent assault for decades. Now if you consider the items below that a hormonal disruption or imbalance would play a role in, it seems like EDC's might be having a huge impact on us & we're not even noticing because it's happening slowly over the entire course of our lives :
- weight regulation / obesity
-  insulin resistance / diabetes (insulin is a hormone)
- reproduction /conception/infertility  (affects egg quality, ovulation, & embryo implantation in women... sperm count in men (sperm count has decreased by 50% in men globally since the 70's)
-  anxiety/depression/mood swings/fatigue/libido
- acne
- early onset puberty
- perimenopause (early onset  or severity of symptoms)
- thyroid disease
- cognition/brain function (recent studies show hormone fluctuations, esp. estrogen decline in menopause, increases risk of Alzheimer's & dementia in women)

Try the   "Not So Pretty"   docuseries on HBO for an easy to digest intro on the topic.  Trailer here:  https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cDcs6N44Aok
Take care ya'll :)

comment_text: At 15:50 I agree with Peter about watching what you do when you are younger to prevent long term issues as you age. This is one of the reasons I am very careful as parents in what I allow my son to do sport wise. My husband deals with an ankle issue he caused in his teens and deals with now in his fifties and will have to deal with for 20 or more years. I have a shoulder issue in my twenties and ever since I have had issues with it. Our body does keep count and a toll is paid with injuries. Mobility should be a huge focus from thirty on, being able to get up from a seated position on the ground with out your hands and also being able to sit on the ground easily. PFAFs and chemicals are a huge cause of testosterone and hormone disruption, endocrine disruption, immunity compromising all around us from chemicals in convenience foods, body products, drinks, clothes, what we cook our food in. Chemicals are an epidemic that no one wants to look at until it's too late. They have shown we people go more natural ie: old fashion, in what they eat and cook with and clothes, the hormones can recover. Interesting to hear about grip strength, I think that is more of a theory. Grandpa lost most of his grip strength like twenty years before he died at 96. I love peter and everything he does but there's one thing that annoys the hell out of me in this podcast. He establishes guidelines or rather standards in precentiles. EVERYTHING he measures is relative to the rest of the population and not absolute. As an example, what if tommorow the average bone density of a 30 year old drops? What if it already has? The number of young people partaking DEXA scans is incredibly low, based on what exactly was this average set up?

The discussion is so totalitarian but the base to the claims are inaccurate at best.

comment_text:
There is an additional benefit to maintaining muscle mass that even most doctors don’t know about.
Plasma gelsolin (pGelsolin) is primarily synthesized in muscle tissue.
Why is this important?
pGelsolin is a protein that modulates inflammation and can mean the difference between living and dying from an infection or injury.
The therapeutic use of pGelsolin is shortly about to become a turning point in critical care modern medicine as awareness grows and the use of it in a variety of settings becomes FDA approved.
The good news is that we can enhance our overall health by maintaining adequate levels in our blood by having enough muscle mass to maintain healthy levels at all times, especially as we age.
All of the high risk groups for COVID 19 had significantly lower pGelsolin levels prior to infection and were therefore more prone to runaway inflammation.
Our bodies natural ability and mechanisms to prevent disease from taking a foothold, such as macrophages, are also enhanced by healthy pGelsolin levels prior.

Most elderly people have problems getting up off the floor. As a child you spend a lot of time on the floor, adults do not.
Doing yoga / stretching exercises on the floor can improve balance, mobility, flexibility and the ability to get up and down.. 
Just getting up and down to the floor in a controlled manner is difficult for many older adults.
Play with your children on the floor. Bend over, get down and pull weeds in your garden. Play with a pet on the floor.
The more effort you make to work on balance and flexibility will pay dividends as you age.

comment_text: Great episode. Always worth noting when all cause mortality is mentioned is that income is the strongest prediction for all cause mortality. Income itself is no.1, if you put it together with all the positives it's associated with their is scant room for anything else! Those with better incomes have better housing and transport more education and better working conditions. Engage in more healthful lifestyles and have access to better healthcare. All cause is frequently used to show a correlation with non casual factors. When someone uses it be cautious. Also large is the gap for healh span, a girl born in one of the poorer UK postcodes should expect 20years less of healthy life than a little girl born in the wealthier postcodes (about 19yrs diff for little boys) Not that Peters advice isn't really good & worth taking!!!

comment_text: I'm 48, and 180lbs. And I been weight training my entire adult life. As long as you do not injure yourself, and have good form, you will continue to gain strength into your late 40s and 50s. I am stronger now then I use to be, and I'm a strong man. My squat and deadlift use to be the same just 2 years ago, but I now have some knee pain (Runners knee), so I intentionally go lighter on squatting and the pain is 95% gone. I start off with low rep strength training, 3 reps and build up to my 95% max over 4 sets. Then I go into hypertrophy training with 8 to 12 reps to near failure. When I injure myself (usually soft tissue, meaning a muscle pull, slight twinge) I back way off and skip training or lower it way down, but I never ever quit training. I learned to rehab my knee, and I am slowly climbing back up to my squat strength without pain. I'm almost always the strongest man in the gym, and those that are stronger then me are almost always bigger, younger guys. My point here is that strength is the last thing to go in age as long as you train. As a man, I recommend that you make training 5 days a week your life style.

Not only does he stick with whole foods, but uses TRT to compensate for the reduction of hormones in response to exercise - specifically weight training.  Not that HRT/TRT is recommended, namely due to risk for cancer, but a reminder of how relevant hormones are.

FWIW Dr. Sean O'Mara, age 61, is another example of someone that mentions the importance of diet and use of HIIT training to target visceral fat, which he and others say is directly associated with compromised health and inflammation.  He avoids artificial means to compensate - ideally where that strategy continues to work for him.

​@@Chapter-Voice As we age, our hormonal responses aren't as robust, meaning the body becomes less efficient at handling the rapid glucose spikes and inflammatory compounds that often come with processed foods, even if you're exercising. 

These processed foods also often lack the crucial micronutrients and can negatively impact things like your gut health, which plays a significant role in overall well-being. 

Ultimately, it's not just about the amount of food or exercise, but the quality of the fuel you're giving your body, especially as you age and those natural buffers start to diminish.

The last bit can be a rather rude awakening when symptoms begin to manifest, making you question your 
logic and why 'nobody bothered to inform you ahead of time'.

comment_text:
There's a missing piece (as always): the will to adopt and attend to aspects of your physical wellbeing cannot be separated from past history, who is in your life, financial and other stressors. You can have the information and ideas, but you can't erase or always overrule your environmental circumstances - whatever age you are. I am not saying 'just accept' the way things are or will be, I am saying we cannot separate our life history from the energy and will to adopt change. 
Secondly, I know people who've been super fit all their life - who have passed away early or not withstood a sudden illness.
Meanwhile, I know people who smoked, drank and didn't take any supplements - and lived merrily to they passed later in life. 
Not advocating bad lifestyles ;) Just saying, there is a limit to how much you can control. Life shows us this.

My approach to teaching is to focus on helping people fall in love with wanting to be physically healthy first - which does not involve teaching about health. Then once a person becomes interested, I only teach them about VO2 max/Oxygen Efficiency and strength - I have I interviewed more than 100 PhDs from all over the world on my podcast about health, and spent 40 years teach health and physical activity in schools. I’m convinced that most people will never engage in becoming healthy because it seems overly complex. The low hanging fruit is to teach the people who are already obsessed with wanting to be healthy. That’s not most people. The heavy lifting is in finding ways to get people to fall in love with wanting to be physically healthy so I’ll take the action. I love spending time on that aspect and then just having a laser focus on helping them to understand the outrageously high benefit of improving their oxygen efficiency or VO2 Max score. The positive molecular and physiological health adaptations from improving this is off the chart. And then now because I’m 59 I teach people about strength because the benefit of that is also so significant when it comes to hazard ratios. So whilst I love this Doctor’s work, for me as a teacher in appeals to such a narrow band of the population. I learn an enormous amount. But I’m not just interested in the low hanging fruit. I want to find ways to draw more people into the world of wanting to be physically healthy.
author: @newscienceofphysicalhealth2934

I started by sitting in front of a crazy, super bright home made SAD light every morning. This paid off in the evening by causing me to get sleepy from darkness.  I also used herbs, magnesium, low-dose (1mg) melatonin, screen dimming/color apps on all devices, and trazodone starting at 7:30 as a sort of sleep insurance.  Finish eating at least 3 hours before bedtime.  This includes alcohol and really stopping alcohol/beer completely did wonders for losing visceral fat.

video_title: Peter Attia: Anti-aging Cure No One Talks About! 50% Chance You’ll Die In A Year If This Happens!
comment_text:
@PierreDybman  Fair question but the real answer is deeper than food. I reached 700 pounds through years of trauma, emotional neglect, survival-mode cycles, and self-medication. Food was my addiction the same way others run to alcohol, cocaine, gambling, or sex. I didn’t need a dealer I had a drive-thru.

I binged when I felt invisible. I ate sugar like others snorted lines trying to escape a feeling I couldn’t name.

Breaking the addiction wasn’t just about stopping food. It was about confronting the pain behind it. And when I started healing, I had to break my addiction to sugar, too even after I thought I was “on track.”

We all have our cycles. I’m sure you’ve got your bad habits, too. Mine just changed me physically. Yours might be changing you mentally.

But I don’t judge. I transform.

I’ve lost over 200 pounds through fasting, breathwork, movement, and truth. And if sharing my story helps even one person face their own reflection then the weight was never wasted. I hope that answers your question sir.

video_title: Peter Attia: Anti-aging Cure No One Talks About! 50% Chance You’ll Die In A Year If This Happens!
comment_text:
That's awesome! The best piece of advice would be to add in foods that are low calorie and high volume absolutely as much as you can! Chicken breast, white fish, Greek yogurt, cottage cheese, beans, lentils, fermented foods (kimchi sauerkraut), low cal veggies (squash is great, salads like pico), fruit. Find creators online who create low calorie high volume recipes (ice cream, cake, cheese cake, brownies, cookies, etc.). The hardest part of weight loss should be creating recipes that you ACTUALLY enjoy and that are low calorie and high volume. 

Improve your gut microbiome, immune system health, metabolic health (mitochondrial health). You are already improving your insulin sensitivity with fasting. Increase GLP-1 with foods that increase GLP-1 naturally: 1 tbsp yerba mate in tea daily, saturated fat from whole food sources (eggs, beef, oysters, etc. - you don't need much), allulose (no sugar 0 calorie sweetener that is great). Protein has a thermic affect and causes us to burn 25% of calories. With fiber, we do not absorb all of the calories. There are studies showing that those with a healthy gut microbiome excrete more calories. Even if you are eating unhealthy, just add in the health stuff (fiber, fermented foods, high anti-oxidant foods) and it will improve your gut microbiome. I'll eat beans or something high in protein before I eat pizza - this lessons the blood sugar spike plus provides something for my gut microbiome. I'll also opt for omega 3 & raw ginger because they are great for reducing the awful post meal fatigue I get from eating high carb foods, the bloating from digestion.

- Healthy fat (thumb size), fiber, protein each meal
- 1.2-1.6g of protein per kg of body weight (Men and women max out at different weights)
- 2 tbsp to 1-1.5 cups of non-pasteurized kimchi or sauerkraut daily - that is all it takes to improve your gut health. I take kimchi and sauerkraut like a supplement.
- Nutrient dense and high anti-oxidant diet: include foods such as kiwi, pomegranate, wild blueberries (frozen is cheapest and more anti-oxidants), cacao powder (not cocoa powder), broccoli sprouts, beef liver, oysters (beware they can cause food born illness), raw salmon, raw ginger, raw turmeric.
- Sauna and red light therapy (mitored or biomax). These are expensive but if you ever get the chance, people will sell $2000 red light panels on marketplace and other platforms for $800-1200 and saunas between $650 and $800 (don't pay more than this). I added a patio heater to my sauna to make it a hybrid (infrared plus goes to 90C). I live in Canada so those are the Canadian prices, likely lower in the U.S. if that is where you are from.

If you have a hard time changing your diet, JUST work on adding these in. I'm telling you, you won't notice yourself eating less of the other stuff. It'll just happen.

When you break your hip or a large bone, the marrow releases tiny particles of bone into your blood stream. That bone collects into the brain and causes damage. My mom's doctor, when she fell and broke her hip was not at the hospital she went to, but on the phone told us it would be critical that they repair her hip with 24-48 hours. video_title: Peter Attia: Anti-aging Cure No One Talks About! 50% Chance You’ll Die In A Year If This Happens!
comment_text:
The way you eat matters !

Intermittent fasting (IF) is backed by multiple studies showing it helps burn fat, not only due to calorie restriction but also through metabolic adaptations.
	1.	Increased fat burning:
IF promotes lipolysis (fat breakdown) by depleting liver glycogen after ~12–16 hours of fasting, shifting the body to use fat as the main energy source.
→ Tinsley GM, La Bounty PM. (2015). Intermittent fasting and its effects on body composition and clinical health markers in humans. Nutr Rev.
	2.	Improved insulin sensitivity:
IF enhances insulin sensitivity, which improves glucose regulation and promotes fat metabolism.
→ Sutton EF et al. (2018). Early Time-Restricted Feeding Improves Insulin Sensitivity, Blood Pressure, and Oxidative Stress. Cell Metab.
	3.	Fat loss even without strict calorie counting:
In some studies, IF resulted in greater fat loss despite similar caloric intake compared to control groups.
→ Trepanowski JF et al. (2017). Effects of Alternate-Day Fasting vs Daily Calorie Restriction. JAMA Intern Med.
	4.	Fasting triggers metabolic pathways (like AMPK and autophagy), helping the body utilize fat more efficiently.
	5.	When combined with a ketogenic diet, IF can help reverse insulin resistance.
Both IF and keto reduce insulin levels and promote fat metabolism. In combination, they may restore insulin sensitivity and reduce markers of metabolic syndrome.
→ Hartman AL et al. (2007). The neuropharmacology of the ketogenic diet. Pediatr Neurol.
→ Paoli A et al. (2013). Beyond weight loss: a review of the therapeutic uses of very-low-carbohydrate (ketogenic) diets. Eur J Clin Nutr.
→ Longo VD, Panda S. (2016). Fasting, circadian rhythms, and time-restricted feeding in healthy lifespan. Cell Metab.

IF not only helps with calorie control but also improves how your body metabolizes fat and sugar. Pairing it with a ketogenic or low-carb diet can significantly enhance these effects—potentially reversing insulin resistance.

comment_text:
@@teresacerna1612 it is not easy, but doable to move the needle on osteoporosis. Your bones are always in transition of building and breaking down due to stimulus. (Osteoclasts and osteoblasts are something to learn about).  My sister is doing it and I’m working on it. Some things we’re doing:
1. Replace lost estrogen. You can even start in your 60’s.  It will help it not get worse.
2. Take sugar out of your diet…now.  It truly messes with your biochemistry. Calcium may be drawn away from bones and into the bloodstream to perform biochemical reactions. (To buffer acidic states created by sugar is just one).
3.  Get oxalates out of your diet.  They are very unstable molecules that can leach out calcium to “become complete”  . The worst offenders are toxic superfoods (spinach, beets, almonds to name a few)
4.  Find ways to jump.  Start small—bones MUST have force placed upon them to build (our friends, the osteoblasts).  I started with stomping.  :)
5.  Lift HEAVY weights! Starting where you can and working with a trainer at least at first to avoid injury. This is critical.
Note: It s our opinion that pharma is not the solution, but I will leave that with you to research.
All the best—you absolutely can improve your bone status!

People have mentioned blue-blockers and turning off devices which emit blue light (screens), before bedtime, where that will trigger melatonin production.

video_title: Peter Attia: Anti-aging Cure No One Talks About! 50% Chance You’ll Die In A Year If This Happens!
comment_text:
Im only 5 minutes into the video, but i just moved into a senior living home for 55 and up. I'm 64 and still active. But living here scares me. 

Most people here have given up. The majority don't do anything because of what he said.  They hurt too much or are afraid of injury.  

I ask the people in their 70s and 80s when they felt they were slowing down. Many said in their late 60s. Some are my age and they seem older due to stroke, some have injuries in the past or some seem scared.

I'm 64 and have recovered from a torn shoulder from lifting 65lb dumbbell on incline. I've had eye surgery last year and torn a calf muscle too,BUT I still workout.  (Lol, I'm slowing down, i think because I live here😢). 

But when I do go to the gym, every 3 days now, instead of every other day,  i do yoga, ride an exercise bike,  do full range of motion on my deadlift,  squats,  bench ect. 

My squats are 400lbs plus, and so are my deadlifts. My preacher dumbbell curl is 60lb 6 reps. 

My cardio has a lot to be desired, but im working on it. 

I currently ride my 1400cc Kawasaki concouse and plan to get back into paddleboarding in Coronado Bay this summer.  

I'm scared that I'll become my neighbors in the senior living home. Maybe I should go back to being homeless in my car. 

I hope to find a job soon. I think it will help me stay active and moving. 

Now, back to the video.✌️🙏😊
author: @leodegas7731

comment_text:
@@victoriassecretisluv i have been homeless for 11 years and had a 85 year old friend who was homeless for many years.  

He has family,  but he said the same thing as you. Unfortunately,  he had to go to a senior home that he can't leave easily because he falls now and can't keep his head up right.  

I used to have arguments with him, to get off the streets.  He didn't want to be a burden and he wanted his freedom.  But he didn't accept  that we other homeless people were the ones protecting him. Finding his keys and phone for him. Finally after one too many falls, he had to move to a senior home.  So many people were using him for his money and car to store things in. They did drugs in his car. He did thank me for worrying about him. I'm told, he misses his freedom.  

I live in a home for active seniors. So we can get out any time of day or night. 

This place is only for 8 months.  If I don't find a job, I will be forced to go back to the streets. But its better than nothing.  And it's a chance to get healthier in a studio apartment with a level bed and proper food for now.

God bless everyone 🙏 . And keep working out 💪😁.
